                        <par_12
                            jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                            sling:resourceType="wcm/foundation/components/parsys">
                            <container4
                                cq:styleIds="[1653545847150,1653242825678,1653545825687,1653545835982]"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/container/v2/container">
                                <title2
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1651545824678,1651545825694]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2024-04-22T13:52:28.125-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="VALENSX5"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    jcr:title="A life-changing moment"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/title/v2/title"
                                    type="h2"
                                    variant="h"/>
                                <text2
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1659545835858]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-21T16:15:01.833-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="jewitca"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>At age 18, Sophia Dempsey had a stroke.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>During a routine day in 2010, the then-college student felt ill and decided to stay home from class. Her boyfriend at the time, Joe, didn’t hear from her the next morning, so he checked on her and found her unresponsive. She was rushed to the hospital where she remained unconscious for two weeks. When she woke, she had little control over her body – and little hope of recovery.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>“Initially, the outlook was extremely negative,” Joe, now Sophia’s husband, says. “[The doctors] explained that there had been quite a lot of damage done to her brain and that those parts of the brain could never recover.”&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                            </container4>
                            <image
                                jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-24T15:02:22.657-05:00"
                                jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-24T15:03:08.409-05:00"
                                jcr:lastModifiedBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/image/v2/image"
                                alt="Abbvie World Stroke"
                                altValueFromDAM="false"
                                displayPopupTitle="true"
                                fileReference="/content/dam/abbvie-com2/images/stories/life-after-stroke-living-with-and-researching-spasticity/AbbVie_World_Stroke_Day_StoryLab.gif"
                                isDecorative="false"
                                titleValueFromDAM="true"/>
                            <container
                                cq:styleIds="[1653545825687,1653545847150,1653242825678,1653545835982]"
                                jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-24T15:03:25.633-05:00"
                                jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-24T15:03:25.633-05:00"
                                jcr:lastModifiedBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/container/v2/container">
                                <separator
                                    cq:styleIds="[1662756423318]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2023-03-29T09:56:55.380-04:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-03-29T09:56:55.380-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/separator/v2/separator"/>
                                <text2_587052927
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1659545835858]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-24T15:06:20.277-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="schafsm"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>Facing an uncertain future, Sophia left the hospital to continue her post-stroke journey. As she acclimated to her new situation, one debilitating challenge emerged among others: spasticity, or muscle stiffness and tightness,&lt;sup>1&lt;/sup> that became severe enough to crack Sophia’s arm splint in half. Spasticity can result from damage to areas of the brain and spinal cord – a possible consequence of stroke – that control muscle and stretch reflexes.&lt;sup>2&lt;/sup>&lt;/p>&#xa;&lt;p>Sophia’s care plan, developed in partnership with her health care providers, has been instrumental in helping her address spasticity, reflecting the importance of managing post-stroke symptoms. And with current and potential research strategies, the future of post-stroke spasticity care is evolving – but there are still gaps in understanding the condition and how to help people identify and tackle it.&lt;sup>3&lt;/sup>&lt;/p>&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                                <separator_copy
                                    cq:styleIds="[1662756423318]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2023-03-29T09:56:55.380-04:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-03-29T09:56:55.380-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/separator/v2/separator"/>
                                <title2
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1651545824678,1651545825694]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2024-04-22T13:52:39.112-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="VALENSX5"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    jcr:title="Consistency and education are key"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/title/v2/title"
                                    type="h2"
                                    variant="h"/>
                                <text2
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1659545835858]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-24T15:14:05.934-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="schafsm"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>One area of need in spasticity research concerns the lack of a universal definition of the condition and therefore inconsistent disease-measuring,&lt;sup>3&lt;/sup> which makes finding the right care plan for people such as Sophia difficult. Dr. Gavin Williams, practicing physiotherapist and associate professor of physiotherapy rehabilitation, Epworth HealthCare and University of Melbourne, says he and his team have consolidated more than two dozen existing clinical practice guidelines – trying to bring consistency to approaching and administering post-stroke spasticity care.&lt;/p>&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                            </container>
